Problem Statement

It’s admission season at Bright Future School. A long line of students is waiting to be registered, and the school needs your help to maintain a clean digital record.

You are given the basic details of multiple students standing in the queue. Your task is to store their information using an array of structures and then display all the records in order.

Input Format

The input consists of:

1. First line:

An integer N → the number of students.
2. Next 3 × N lines:

For each student, enter:

Line 1 → Student’s name (no spaces)
Line 2 → Student’s age (integer)
Line 3 → Student’s grade (single uppercase letter)
Constraints

Name length ≤ 50
3 ≤ Age ≤ 20
Grade is a single uppercase letter (A–F)
Output Format

For each student, print the details in the following order:

Student i:

Name: name

Age: age

Grade: grade
Here i is the student’s position in the input list

Print the details of each student one after another

Do not add extra text or symbols

Sample Input 0

2
Meena
10
A
Arjun
14
B
Sample Output 0

Student 1:
Name: Meena
Age: 10
Grade: A
Student 2:
Name: Arjun
Age: 14
Grade: B









#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Student{
    char name[50];
    int age;
    char grade;
    
};
int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    struct Student s[n];
    
    for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
        scanf("%s", s[i].name);
        scanf("%d", &s[i].age);
        scanf(" %c", &s[i].grade);
    }
    for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
        printf("Student %d:\n", i+1);
        printf("Name: %s\n", s[i].name);
        printf("Age: %d\n", s[i].age);
        printf("Grade: %c\n", s[i].grade);
    }

        
    return 0;
}




